    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm kinda handy so i'd rather try to fix it myself before calling someone expensive. if it's a capacitor issue, how do i check it? is there anything specific i should look for when i open the panel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you're determined to try fixing it, you'll need to be extremely careful, as these units deal with high voltage, so *always* turn off the power at the breaker first. A bad capacitor often looks swollen, leaking, or has visible scorch marks, which are signs of failure. If you have a multimeter, you can check the capacitance value against the rating printed on the capacitor itself. However, even a quick inspection requires electrical knowledge, so proceed with caution.",
